        {
            "key": "research:counting numbers",
            "value": "In mathematics, the natural numbers are those used for counting and ordering. In common mathematical terminology, words colloquially used for counting are \"cardinal numbers\", and words used for ordering are \"ordinal numbers\". The natural numbers can, at times, appear as a convenient set of codes, that is, as what linguists call nominal numbers, forgoing many or all of the properties of being a number in a mathematical sense. Some definitions, including the standard ISO 80000-2, begin the natural numbers with 0, corresponding to the non-negative integers 0, 1, 2, 3,..., whereas others start ...",
